# Linux Networking & Protocols

Below are the Linux Networking & Protocols.

1. OSI & TCP/IP
The OSI model describes how data travels across a network in 7 layers.

---------------------------------------------
|7 --> Application  --> HTTP, FTP, DNS      |
|6 --> Presentation --> SSL/TLS, encoding   |
|5 --> Session      --> session mgmt        |
|4 --> Transport    --> TCP, UDP            |
|3 --> Network      --> IP, routing         |
|2 --> Data Link    --> MAC, switches       |
|1 --> Physical     --> cables, NICs        |
---------------------------------------------

2. IP & Subnetting
Every device on a network needs an address. Subnetting tells you which devices can talk to each other directly.

ip a        --> show your IP addresses (modern)
ifconfig    --> show network interfaces (older)
ip route    --> show your routing table
hostname -I --> quick way to see your IP

3. DNS & HTTP
DNS translates names to IPs.

nslookup google.com      --> resolve a domain to an IP
dig google.com           --> detailed DNS lookup
dig google.com MX        --> look up mail servers
whois google.com         --> domain registration info
curl -I https://site.com --> view HTTP response headers
curl https://site.com    --> fetch raw page content

4. TCP/UDP & Ports
Port 21   --> FTP
Port 22   --> SSH
Port 23   --> Telnet
Port 25   --> SMTP (email)
Port 53   --> DNS
Port 80   --> HTTP
Port 443  --> HTTPS
Port 445  --> SMB (Windows file sharing)
Port 3389 --> RDP (Windows remote desktop)

5. Nmap
It's how you discover what's alive on a network and what's running on it.

nmap 192.168.1.1        --> basic scan of a single host
nmap 192.168.1.0/24     --> scan an entire subnet
nmap -sV target         --> detect service versions
nmap -sS target         --> stealth SYN scan
nmap -O target          --> guess the OS
nmap -A target          --> aggressive scan (OS+version+scripts)
nmap -p- target         --> scan all 65535 ports
nmap -sn 192.168.1.0/24 --> ping scan only (find live hosts)
Only scan networks/hosts you own or have explicit written permission to test (e.g. TryHackMe, HackTheBox, your own home lab VMs)
Use yown device IP Address please

6. Wireshark
Wireshark lets you see every packet flowing across a network. It turns abstract protocols into something you can actually watch happen.

wireshark               --> launch the GUI
tcpdump -i eth0         --> capture packets from terminal
tcpdump -i eth0 port 80 --> capture only HTTP traffic
http                    --> Wireshark filter: show only HTTP
ip.addr == 192.168.1.5  --> filter by IP address
tcp.port == 443         --> filter by port

